08729nam a22009615i 9789048559381DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485593817 a10.1515/97890485593812doi  a(DE-B1597)647561  a(OCoLC)1371972255  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a952.04223//eng/20230707eng00aReconsidering Postwar Japanese History :bA Handbook /ced. by Simon Avenell. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHandbooks on Japanese Studies00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tContributors -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Imagining Japan’s Postwar Era -- tPart 1: The Origins of the Postwar -- t1 Rethinking Imperial Legacies and the Cold War in Allied Occupied Japan -- t2 Money, Banking, and Fiscal Reforms in Allied Occupied Japan, 1945–1952 -- tPart 2: The Political Postwar -- t3 Arguing with Public Opinion: Polls and Postwar Democracy -- t4 Japanese Postwar Political History from Left to Right -- t5 Nationalism under the Banner of Pacifism: Japanese Atomic Bombing Sufferers’ Struggle against the State -- t6 Living with and Fighting against the Postwar Regime: Conservatism and Constitution in Postwar Japan -- tPart 3: Postwar Culture and Society -- t7 Gendering Postwar Japan -- t8 Uncertain Futures, Destabilized Dreams -- t9 Education in Japan since 1945: Equality, Hierarchy, and Competition -- t10 From Raincoats to Ketchup: The Encroachment of Plastics during the High-growth Era (1955–1973) -- t11 Birds and Children as Barometers of Japan’s Postwar Environmental History -- t12 Japan’s Got Talent: The Rise of Tarento in Japanese Television Culture -- tPart 4: The Transnational Postwar -- t13 Postwar Japanese Feminism in Transnational Perspective -- t14 Postwar Japanese History Seen through the Science of Reproductive and Population Politics -- tPart 5: Japan’s Postwar in Asia and the World -- t15 Japan’s American Alliance: Forgoing Autonomy for Deterrence -- t16 The Endless Postwar: Okinawa at the Modern Frontier -- t17 Orders, Borders and Japan’s Identity -- t18 Manga, National Identity and Internationalization in Postwar Japan -- tPart 6: Defining, Delineating, Historicizing and Chronologizing the Postwar Era -- t19 Discourses of War and Peace during Japan’s “Postwar” -- t20 Postwar in the Post-Cold War: Postwar in the Heisei Era -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter war defeat in 1945, Japan underwent historic political, economic and social transformations resulting in the country’s rebirth as an economic powerhouse and exemplar of liberal democracy in East Asia. This handbook expands and enriches our understanding of this tumultuous contemporary era in Japan’s modern history. Chapters in the volume ask novel theoretical questions and present fresh empirical perspectives on the era. How, for example, has the postwar era been chronologized to date and how might we rethink or enhance such interpretations? What can we learn by rethinking established moments and phases like the Allied Occupation, the period of high-speed economic growth, the 1970s, the Bubble Economy, and the “lost decades” of Heisei Japan (1989-2019)? What new issues might we introduce to subvert accepted understandings of the postwar era and its various sub-eras? Moreover, how might Japan’s internal postwar be expanded by rethinking the era through novel historical frameworks and regional imaginaries such as East Asian history, Cold War history, environmental history and transnational history? Contributors attempt to transcend temporal, geographical, intellectual and other boundaries inherent in our current understandings of Japan’s postwar experience to provide a compelling compilation of perspectives. Showcasing the work of historians and leading scholars from other disciplines, chapters cover thematic areas including the origins of the postwar era, postwar politics, society and popular culture, transnational and international interactions, and historical memory. The volume’s extensive chronological coverage, combined with the innovative perspectives of the contributors, make it essential reading for both researchers and learners interested in the multifaceted dynamics of Japan’s fascinating contemporary era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies. 4aContemporary Society. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aPolitics and Government. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  aJapan, Japanese History, Postwar History.1 aAvenell, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvenell, Simon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBabb, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorland, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBronson, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBullock, Julia C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBytheway, Simon James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCave, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, Deokhyo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCwiertka, Katarzyna J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnvall, H.D.P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranks, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHara, Kimie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHomei, Aya, econtributor.4